entry.title: Resolve races between `PRE_UNSUBSCRIBE` and organic actions.
entry.content:
After the user taps the `PRE_UNSUBSCRIBE` action on a notification, we

need to complete native startup before we can replace the tapped

notification with the "provisionally unsubscribed" service notification.



In this time window, the user might have tapped the content or a

developer-provided action button. Given the strong indication the user

may want to stop getting these notifications, resolve this conflict by

silently discarding the action.



Furthermore, if the developer closes the notification the user tapped on

while the service notification is showing in its stead, do not let the

service notification it be canceled. The organic notification is at this

point already deleted from the `NotificationDatabase` in response to it

being closed by the developer. If the user clicks `UNDO_UNSUBSCRIBE`, we

will not restore the cancelled notification.

entry.title: [gbb-cct] Fix bugs.
entry.content:
Fix bug that occurs when TabObserver::onDidFinishNavigationInPrimaryMainFrame is called *before* BaseCustomTabRootUiCoordinator::onFinishNativeInitialization. In this case we never receive a NavigationHandle, and so we never auto-trigger.



For now the fix for this is to remove the code that waits for NavigationHandle before auto-triggering, given a) it may never come, and b) if it's going to come it probably will have happened before auto-trigger happens (at 60 seconds). Auto-triggering without NavigationHandle just causes internal code to provide the most conservative `PageInsightsConfig` options - triggering with these options is better than not triggering at all. Filed b/325597773 to come up with a long-term solution that will allow us to always get NavigationHandle.



Also fix bug where we do not reset on a new tab, and do not register an observer on that new tab.



Also add some new logging statements to aid future debugging.

entry.title: Modify GetOwningForm to handle nested shadow DOM forms.
entry.content:
Prior to this CL, GetOwning form would return the nearest shadow-

including ancestor of a form control element (given that the form

control element was not associated with a form inside its shadow DOM).



This no longer works for forms that are nested (in a shadow-including

sense): Once kAutofillIncludeFormElementsInShadowDom is enabled,

only top level forms are considered: A top level form will own all

form control elements of forms that are descendants of it.

As a result, GetOwningForm must return the furthest shadow-including

ancestor.



This CL makes this change (gated behind the

kAutofillIncludeFormElementsInShadowDom feature) and adds tests for it.

entry.title: [1/n] Fix TabDragging tests for fallback tab dragging: DragAll
entry.content:
This is part of a series of CLs to make the TabDragging tests pass with

fallback tab dragging, i.e. with the AllowWindowDragUsingSystemDragDrop

feature enabled. The goal is for all tests that pass with the current

tab dragging implementation to pass with fallback tab dragging as well,

so that it can be enabled by default.



This CL adjusts the expectations of

TabDragging/DetachToBrowserTabDragControllerTest.DragAll to match what

is possible on Linux ozone/wayland.



The test expects the browser to be moved down if we drag all tabs, but

that doesn’t work with fallback tab dragging (we can’t both start a DnD

session, which we need for merging with other windows, and an

interactive move; that’s what we need the extended-drag protocol for).

Thus, we change the test to only expect the browser bounds to change if

we can control them.



Note that the test passes without this change using the current tab

dragging implementation (i.e. when fallback tab dragging is disabled),

but it shouldn’t. When you run the test non-headless, you can see that

the window doesn’t really move; the test just thinks it has moved

because `GetBounds()` returns the bounds that were set using

`SetBounds()`, even though that had no actual effect on the window’s

position.

downloaded files are moved to their final location once the associated

ExternalVideoEncoder copies a video frame if its storage type is not

STORGAE_SHMEM or the frame coded size doesn't match.

ExternalVideoEncoder gets always STRAGE_UNOWNED_MEMORY and thus the

vide the video frame is copied always.

The display capture stack should be producing SharedMemory VideoFrame.

It is VideoCaptureClient that converts it to STORAGE_UNOWNED_MEMORY.

This fixes the conversion and prevents the unnecessary video frame

copy.



This saves approximately 100mW (9.17W->9.07W) in power consumption and

reduces the encode time by 1ms (14.4ms->13.4ms) on brya.

entry.title: [//gpu] Add `texture_target_exception_list` to SharedImageCapabilities
entry.content:
This addition will facilitate porting clients' obtaining the texture

target to use to go through ClientSharedImage and eliminating the

existing mess of functions via which clients currently do so. Once this

port happens, we will remove `texture_target_exception_list` from

Capabilities.



This field is populated in the same way that it is in Capabilities,

from the corresponding field in GpuPreferences. With one exception,

the GpuPreferences that the two structs operate on come from the same

place: the GPUService. There is one case where the source is different,

however: that when InProcessCommandBuffer is used. In that case, the

DecoderContexts (which initialize

Capabilities::texture_target_exception_list from their passed-in

GpuPreferences) are using the GpuPreferences that are created here [1].

SharedImageFactory, however, is always using the GpuPreferences that

come from the GPUService itself. Fortunately, InProcessCommandBuffer is

only used in testing contexts.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:gpu/ipc/in_process_gpu_thread_holder.cc;l=28;drc=d25fb50ead28da7a369d241521590053e7dd13bd;bpv=1;bpt=1

entry.title: [//gpu] Change how ProduceSkia() chooses Ganesh vs. Graphite
entry.content:
SharedImageBacking::ProduceSkia() currently assumes that if the

GrContext is not present, then we are using Graphite and hence

graphite_context() should be present. However, this is not universally

true (see [1]). This CL changes this function to go to Ganesh or

Graphite based on the GrContextType.



Note: Before Graphite was introduced into this function, there was

nothing checking that the GrContext was non-null [1]. Hence, this CL

also does not introduce any such check. Any issues that come up in

individual backings will now be properly surfaced as crashes at the

level of those individual backings. This CL *does* add a CHECK that

the GrContextType on a call to ProduceSkia() is not `kNone`. When the

GrContextType is `kNone` Skia initialization is skipped, meaning that

both gr_context() and graphite_context() will be null. Hence, we would

already be hitting the current CHECK(graphite_context()) in this case.



[1] https://issues.chromium.org/u/1/issues/41495250#comment5

[2] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4480449

entry.title: Fix dangling pointer issues in system_signals_service unittests.
entry.content:
The constructors for these unittests create a MockFileSystemService

sub-object owned by a unique_ptr and moves them to

`${platform_}system_signals_service_`. The test holds on to the

sub-objects via raw_ptr.



This causes dangling pointer detection to fire during test destruction

as the ordering of the member variable (in the unittest) causes the

owning object to be destroyed first (thus making the sub-object

dangling -- for an instant).



Re-ordering the raw_ptr sub-object such that it is destroyed first

avoids this problem.

entry.content:
The current PickerItemView is only for items that are displayed in a

"list item" format (e.g. urls, files), so rename it accordingly.



In a followup, we will add a separate base class PickerItemView (which

can be a list item, emoji item, image item, etc.) to support shared

functionality between different item types, e.g. highlighting the item

during keyboard navigation.
